I'm upgrading a large legacy code base to use to Lodash 4.  This project uses a (somewhat questionable) practice where property getters return promises.  Something like this:

```ts
export class DataModel {
  public get object1(): Promise<string> {
    // Performs a network call, returns a promise
    return this._fetchRestApiResult("https://example.com/object1");
  }
  public get object2(): Promise<number> {
    // Performs a network call, returns a promise
    return this._fetchRestApiResult("https://example.com/object2");
  }
}

interface IFetchedData {
  object1: string;
  object2: number;
}

export class ViewLayer {
  private dataModel: DataModel;

  public render(): void {
    Promise.props(_.pick(this.dataModel, ["object1", "object2"]))
      .then((result: IFetchedData) => {
        console.log(`Got: object1=${result.object1} object2=${result.object2}`);
      });
  }
}
```

**Expected:** In Lodash 2, `_.pick(this.dataModel, ["object1", "object2"])` works fine. The property getters are called once, and then `Promise.props()` waits for the promises to resolve, and then returns the combined result.

**Actual:** In Lodash 4, `_.pick` reads the property getters twice.  This means the first promise chain gets discarded, which causes a number of bad effects:
- The network request may be performed twice, which is inefficient
- The back-to-back calls sometimes reveal a race condition in the implementation
- If the promise chain rejects, we get an uncaught exception failure, because the promise chain was not properly terminated

Lodash doesn't make any formal guarantee about how many reads are performed.  But it would be reasonable for developers to assume the implementation should avoid obviously redundant operations.  It's fairly common for property getters to do nontrivial calculations (although starting promises is admittedly a bit unusual).  Also, it's surprising that Lodash 4 would be less efficient than Lodash 2.

## What's going on

Looking at the code, `pick()` calls `basePick()`:

[`pick.js`](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/4.17.15-npm/pick.js)
```ts
var pick = flatRest(function(object, paths) {
  return object == null ? {} : basePick(object, paths);
});
```

...and `basePick()` calls `basePickBy()`:

[_basePick.js](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/4.17.15-npm/_basePick.js)
```ts
function basePick(object, paths) {
  return basePickBy(object, paths, function(value, path) {
    return hasIn(object, path);
  });
}
```

Then `basePickBy()` calls `baseGet()`:

[_basePickBy.js](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/4.17.15-npm/_basePickBy.js)
```ts
function basePickBy(object, paths, predicate) {
  var index = -1,
      length = paths.length,
      result = {};

  while (++index < length) {
    var path = paths[index],
        value = baseGet(object, path);

    if (predicate(value, path)) {
      baseSet(result, castPath(path, object), value);
    }
  }
  return result;
}
```

And `baseGet()` ultimately reads the value:

[_baseGet.js](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/4.17.15-npm/_baseGet.js)
```ts
function baseGet(object, path) {
  path = castPath(path, object);

  var index = 0,
      length = path.length;

  while (object != null && index < length) {
    object = object[toKey(path[index++])];  // <=== GETTER READ #1
  }
  return (index && index == length) ? object : undefined;
}
```

For the second read, `basePickBy()` invokes the `predicate(value, path)` which calls `hasIn(object, path)` from **_basePick.js** above:

[hasIn.js](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/4.17.15-npm/hasIn.js)
```ts
function hasIn(object, path) {
  return object != null && hasPath(object, path, baseHasIn);
}
```

This calls `hasPath()` which finally performs the read:

[_hasPath.js](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/4.17.15-npm/_hasPath.js)
```ts
function hasPath(object, path, hasFunc) {
  path = castPath(path, object);

  var index = -1,
      length = path.length,
      result = false;

  while (++index < length) {
    var key = toKey(path[index]);
    if (!(result = object != null && hasFunc(object, key))) {
      break;
    }
    object = object[key];  // <=== GETTER READ #2
  }
  if (result || ++index != length) {
    return result;
  }
  length = object == null ? 0 : object.length;
  return !!length && isLength(length) && isIndex(key, length) &&
    (isArray(object) || isArguments(object));
}
```

## Proposed fix

This loop seems to evaluate `object = object[key];` pointlessly:

[_hasPath.js](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/4.17.15-npm/_hasPath.js)
```ts
  while (++index < length) {
    var key = toKey(path[index]);
    if (!(result = object != null && hasFunc(object, key))) {
      break;
    }
    object = object[key];  // <=== GETTER READ #2
  }
  if (result || ++index != length) {
    return result;
  }
```
When `hasFunc()` returns true, then `result` becomes `true`, which ensures that we will call `return result;`.  Thus the `object[key]` value is never used.

So it seems we could avoid the second read by optimizing this logic in `hasPath()`.
